WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.035
Radiograph in Dentistry


00:00:02.035 --> 00:00:03.943
Role of Dental Assistants:


00:00:03.943 --> 00:00:05.761
Taking Dental X-Rays:


00:00:05.761 --> 00:00:12.647
Dental assistants are responsible for capturing high-quality radiographs, which are essential for diagnosing dental conditions.


00:00:12.647 --> 00:00:19.437
They must be skilled in positioning patients and equipment to obtain clear images that accurately represent the patient’s oral health.


00:00:19.437 --> 00:00:22.825
Ensuring Safety Measures for Radiation Exposure:


00:00:22.825 --> 00:00:29.489
It is crucial for dental assistants to implement strict protocols to minimize radiation exposure to patients and themselves.


00:00:29.489 --> 00:00:33.036
This includes using protective equipment such as lead aprons, adhering


00:00:33.036 --> 00:00:37.261
to radiation safety guidelines, and maintaining proper distance during X-ray


00:00:37.261 --> 00:00:38.628
procedures.


00:00:38.628 --> 00:00:39.998
Importance:


00:00:39.998 --> 00:00:45.164
Accurate imaging through dental radiography is vital for effective diagnosis and treatment planning.


00:00:45.164 --> 00:00:52.316
Radiographs provide dentists with essential information about the health of a patient’s teeth, bone structure, and surrounding tissues.


00:00:52.316 --> 00:00:56.736
They help identify issues such as cavities, periodontal disease, and other


00:00:56.736 --> 00:00:59.726
oral health abnormalities that may not be visible during a routine


00:00:59.726 --> 00:01:00.945
examination.


00:01:00.945 --> 00:01:09.107
By facilitating precise diagnostics, dental X-rays play a significant role in developing targeted treatment plans and improving patient outcomes.

